:::summary
Publius Vergilius Maro (70–19 BC), known as Virgil, was the greatest poet of ancient Rome — the author of the *Aeneid*, the Roman national epic; the *Eclogues*, pastoral poems of haunting beauty; and the *Georgics*, a magnificent poem on farming and the Italian countryside. His *Aeneid* told the founding myth of Rome through the Trojan hero Aeneas and became the central text of Latin education for two thousand years. Virgil's influence on Western literature is second only to [Homer](article.html?id=homer): [Dante](article.html?id=dante) made him his guide through Hell and Purgatory, [Milton](article.html?id=john-milton) wrote *Paradise Lost* in conscious dialogue with the *Aeneid*, and every subsequent tradition of European epic poetry stands in his shadow.
:::

